      <h1 class="mf-title">For School Leaders</h1>
      <p class="mf-subtitle mf-copy">We made the film <i>Most Likely To Succeed</i> to help school leaders effect change.  We’re seeing inspiring examples all over the country where a leader brings their community together to watch the film, hosts a vibrant discussion after the film, and polls attendees on questions of relevance to their go-forward strategy.  After seeing this film, the audience understands the urgency for moving forward, and is inspired by what is possible.  What we hear back is that the film enables bold initiatives to take place -- at the school, district, or state level -- that otherwise would shrivel on the vine.</p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Numbered List Container Start -->
  <section class="copy-container moving-forward-copy numbered-list-container">
    <div class="big-wrapper">
      <h2 class="mf-header mf-section-header mf-section-header no-bpadding">At the school level, the following sequence can produce inspiring results:</h2>
    </div>
    <div class="wrapper small-numbered-list">
      <ul class="numbered-list">
        <li class="numbered-list-item">
          <div class="item-content-container">
            <span class="number list-order-indicator">1</span>
            <p class="list-copy numbered-item-copy"> Organize a community screening with the film <i>Most Likely To Succeed</i>.  You’ll be glad you started with this.  We’ll help support you in turning this into a big school event (perhaps even a fundraiser), and generate  excitement about the future of your school.  Your audience will be energized for a post-film Q&A session, and you’ll want to pick the right person (or panel) to facilitate this discussion. You may want to prepare a set of polling questions for attendees, which will help you begin to build the support for effecting real change.</p>
          </div>
        </li>
        <li class="numbered-list-item">
          <div class="item-content-container">
            <span class="number list-order-indicator">2</span>
            <p class="list-copy numbered-item-copy">Build on the momentum from an initial screening by bringing your community back together for a follow-on session designed to build a consensus around what outcomes you want your school to achieve for its students. <a href="#build-consensus" class="nav-scroll black-copy-link">Build Consensus</a></p>
          </div>
        </li>
        <li class="numbered-list-item">
          <div class="item-content-container">
            <span class="number list-order-indicator">3</span>
            <p class="list-copy numbered-item-copy">As your school moves forward, consider working with some of our <a href="#" class="black-copy-link">partner organizations</a> who have deep expertise in helping schools transform.</p>
          </div>
        </li>
      </ul>
    </div>
  </section>
  <!-- Numbered List Container End -->

  <!-- Building Consesus Section Start -->
  <section id="build-consensus" class="copy-container moving-forward-copy numbered-list-container">
    <div class="wrapper no-bpadding">
      <h2 class="mf-header mf-section-header">Building Consensus</h2>
      <p class="mf-copy no-bpadding">After a school-wide screening of <i>Most Likely To Succeed</i>, many school communities want to bring their community back together and build on the emerging momentum.  We’ve had great results with a follow-on session that helps build a consensus in your school community about desired outcomes and design principles for the future of your school.  Clearly, you’ll modify what’s below to suit your community’s needs, but it goes like this:</p>
    </div>
    <div class="wrapper small-numbered-list">
      <ul class="numbered-list">
        <li class="numbered-list-item">
          <div class="item-content-container">
            <span class="number list-order-indicator">1</span>
            <p class="list-copy numbered-item-copy">Start by showing this ten-minute clip from <a href="https://vimeo.com/135611275" class="black-copy-link" target="_blank">this film</a>. It sets the stage for the session, brings those who haven’t seen the film a bit up to speed, and is a great refresher for those who already have seen the film.</p>
          </div>
        </li>
        <li class="numbered-list-item">
          <div class="item-content-container">
            <span class="number list-order-indicator">2</span>
            <p class="list-copy numbered-item-copy">As an initial exercise, have your audience break into smaller teams (say, about ten-ish) and address the following question, and then share their responses:</p>
            <p class="list-copy numbered-item-copy sub-num-copy"><em>When you reflect on your time in school, describe a person, idea, or experience that changed your future and what you’re capable of.</em></p>
            <p class="list-copy numbered-item-copy sub-num-copy">It can be quite powerful if you get each group to summarize common aspects of their responses. A teacher passionate about a topic? Particular mentors? A club or sports experience? A traditional lecture class, with multiple choice quizzes and exams (something we’ve yet to see!!)?</p>
          </div>
        </li>
        <li class="numbered-list-item">
          <div class="item-content-container">
            <span class="number list-order-indicator">3</span>
            <p class="list-copy numbered-item-copy">Show this <a href="" class="black-copy-link">short clip</a> (3 ½ minute clip from Greg) on skills needed in 1893, and in today’s world.</p>
          </div>
        </li>
        <li class="numbered-list-item">
          <div class="item-content-container">
            <span class="number list-order-indicator">4</span>
            <p class="list-copy numbered-item-copy">Break into groups of 8-12 people and spend about an hour addressing these two questions:</p>
            <p class="list-copy numbered-item-copy sub-num-copy"><em>What do we want our future high school graduates to know and be able to do?</em></p>
            <p class="list-copy numbered-item-copy sub-num-copy"><em>Given the answers to the question above, what are the most important characteristics of the high school of the future?</em></p>
            <p class="list-copy numbered-item-copy sub-num-copy">Then, reconvene as a whole and have each group share its conclusions. You’ll find that this process will align your community in terms of goals.</p>
          </div>
        </li>
        <li class="numbered-list-item">
          <div class="item-content-container">
            <span class="number list-order-indicator">5</span>
            <p class="list-copy numbered-item-copy">In this (or a follow-on) session, have your community take on the following issues.</p>
            <p class="list-copy numbered-item-copy sub-num-copy"><em>Given the skills and characteristics we’ve identified as priorities for our students, what process could we use to evaluate how we’re doing relative to these priorities. Where there are gaps? How do we begin to close them?</em></p>
            <p class="list-copy numbered-item-copy sub-num-copy"><em>In the past few years, what are our success cases for innovation?  Where have our efforts to innovate proven unsuccessful?  What are three things we could do to encourage innovation and change throughout our school?</em></p>
            <p class="list-copy numbered-item-copy sub-num-copy">For the person or team moderating this event, you may want to check out this <a href="" class="black-copy-link">short video</a> from Stephanie Rogen, CEO of Greenwich Leadership Partners, who is one of the top facilitators in the country, with real expertise in leading sessions like this.</p>
          </div>
        </li>
      </ul>
    </div>
  </section>
